{"actor":{"id":"claude-fable-5","type":"agent"},"content":{"blocks":[{"text":"Good calls all around — and B-as-test-oracle is a genuinely nice idea: run gitleaks/trufflehog rulesets (and their test corpora) against our redaction output in CI, so \"A is complete enough\" becomes a measurable claim instead of a vibe. Agreed on C being opt-in off-by-default; `.env`-as-plain-config is common enough that silent masking would corrupt records for no benefit.\n\nHere's E concretely.\n\n## What E actually is: a tripwire at `cledger sync`\n\nToday, `sync` does three things: fetch the remote notes ref, merge it with `cat_sort_uniq`, push the local notes ref. E inserts a scan between merge and push. Walking through a real scenario:\n\n1. **During a session**, the agent runs `cat config.yml` and the tool result contains `db_password: hunter2xK9!`. Capture-time rules (A) don't touch it — there's no `ghp_`/`AKIA`-style prefix, and A is deliberately conservative. The event lands in your local notes verbatim. That's fine: it's on your disk, next to the plaintext transcript in `~/.claude` that already contains the same string.\n\n2. **Weeks later you run `cledger sync`** — the moment the record is about to leave your machine. Sync diffs the local notes ref against what the remote already has and scans *only the not-yet-pushed events*. Because a human is present and nothing gets rewritten automatically, this scan can afford the noisy rules that A can't: entropy heuristics, `password=`/`secret:` keyword patterns, connection-string shapes.\n\n3. **On a hit, the push aborts** and you see each finding: event id, conversation, timestamp, and the snippet with the match highlighted. Two ways forward:\n   - **False positive** → allowlist it (persisted by finding fingerprint, so the same string never nags again) and re-sync.\n   - **Real secret** → `cledger redact <event-id>`, then sync proceeds clean.\n\n## Why the sync boundary is special: purge is still cheap there\n\nThis is the part that makes E more than a nag screen. The notes ref is a commit chain — every append creates a new notes commit, and `git push` sends the *whole reachable history*, old blobs included. So \"removing\" a secret from the current note while old note blobs remain reachable does nothing once pushed.\n\nBut **pre-push, the local notes history belongs to nobody but you**. A redact-before-first-push can rewrite the note line *and* squash the local notes ref into a single fresh commit (notes history has essentially no value worth preserving), making the secret-bearing blob genuinely unreachable before anything leaves the machine. Post-push, the same operation requires a force-push and every collaborator re-fetching — the hard, coordination-heavy case.\n\nSo the three layers form a cost gradient:\n\n- **A (capture):** prevents the highest-confidence secrets from ever being written. Free.\n- **E (sync):** catches the ambiguous stuff while removal is still a local, trivial operation. Cheap.\n- **Post-push purge (future tooling):** the expensive last resort E exists to keep you out of.\n\nBlock-by-default with an explicit `--no-scan`-style escape hatch, consistent with \"sharing is a deliberate user choice.\"\n\n## Redaction metadata\n\nAgreed on maximal specificity. Concretely, a redaction should leave two artifacts: the in-place placeholder — `[REDACTED:<rule-id>:<fingerprint>]` with rule id, ruleset version, and a truncated keyed fingerprint so identical secrets correlate across events without being recoverable — and a companion `redaction`-kind event (the schema already has the kind and `links.redacts`) recording target event id, rule id + ruleset version, byte offsets/length of what was removed, who/when, and whether it was automatic (A) or human-adjudicated (E). The record stays honest about its own gaps.\n\nWant me to write this up as the redaction section of the technical design doc, or jump straight into implementing A plus the test harness?","type":"text"}],"role":"assistant