{"actor":{"id":"claude-fable-5","type":"agent"},"content":{"blocks":[{"text":"I've read the design docs and the capture path (`src/adapters/claude-code.ts`, `src/store.ts`). Two architectural facts shape everything here, so let me state them first:\n\n1. **The event id is a hash of `content`** (the identity subset), while `raw` is excluded from identity. So any redaction of `content` must be *deterministic* — same source line in, same redacted output out — or rescans break idempotency and duplicate events. Meanwhile `raw` can be scrubbed freely without affecting ids. And critically: redacting `content` but leaving `raw.data` verbatim is theater, since `raw` holds the whole original line.\n2. **The real security boundary is `sync`, not capture.** The native transcripts in `~/.claude/projects/` already sit on disk in plaintext, so capture-time redaction doesn't protect the local machine — it protects the *future shared record*. But once a secret lands in a note, purging is genuinely hard (note history retains prior blobs, and the purge tooling doesn't exist yet), which is why keeping secrets out at capture still matters: prevention is cheap, removal is expensive.\n\nWith that frame, the options:\n\n## A. Built-in pattern rules at capture (structured-token regexes)\n\nGitleaks-style regexes for unambiguous token formats — `ghp_…`, `sk-ant-…`, `AKIA…`, `xoxb-…`, PEM `BEGIN PRIVATE KEY` blocks, JWTs — applied in the adapter before `appendEvents`, replacing matches with a deterministic placeholder like `[REDACTED:github-pat:<fingerprint>]`.\n\n- **Pros:** Zero setup, default-on protection. Prefixed token formats are essentially false-positive-free, which matters enormously given the product commitment to \"preserve exact visible content\" — a false positive is a silent history rewrite, violating your own behavioral commitments. Deterministic, fast, offline.\n- **Cons:** Inherently incomplete — passwords, connection strings, and unprefixed secrets sail through. Ruleset evolution is an id-stability hazard: v2 rules catching what v1 missed means a forced rescan produces different content → different ids → duplicates. (You already accepted exactly this caveat for identity stamping, so it's a known and tolerable cost, but the ruleset needs a version stamp — probably alongside `raw.format`.)\n\n## B. Vendor an existing scanner (gitleaks subprocess, secretlint, trufflehog)\n\n- **Pros:** Maintained, battle-tested rulesets; you don't own the regex arms race.\n- **Cons:** Poor fit for a per-turn Stop hook that must be fast and never fail the session — gitleaks is an external Go binary users would need installed; trufflehog's verification mode phones home (disqualifying for a privacy feature). Upstream ruleset drift makes determinism/versioning worse, not better, since you don't control when rules change. Vendoring the *ruleset* (a pinned copy of gitleaks' TOML patterns) rather than the tool gets most of the benefit without the dependency.\n\n## C. Value-based masking from known secret sources\n\nRead actual secret values from `process.env` and `.env`-style files at capture time, scrub exactly those strings (this is how GitHub Actions' `::add-mask::` works).\n\n- **Pros:** Near-zero false positives *and* catches unstructured secrets that no regex can — the DB password with no telltale prefix. Highest recall-per-risk of any option.\n- **Cons:** Nondeterministic across time and machines — env changes between capture and rescan yield different content, hence different ids. Only protects secrets that happen to live in env/.env. The capture hook itself starts reading sensitive files, which needs care. I'd rank this a strong v2 layer, not the foundation.\n\n## D. User-configured path/pattern exclusion rules\n\nConfig-driven: drop or truncate `tool_result` content for reads of matching paths (`.env`, `*.pem`, `secrets/`), plus user regexes. The design doc already gestures at this.\n\n- **Pros:** Aligns perfectly with \"make sharing, retention, redaction deliberate user choices.\" Deterministic if the config is part of the versioned rule input. Handles repo-specific secrets no built-in list can know about. Path-based exclusion (\"never record the contents of `.env` reads\") is higher-precision than content scanning.\n- **Cons:** Default-off means most users get nothing. Config location is a real question: committed (`.cledger.toml`) shares team policy but advertises where the secrets are; local-only doesn't travel. Also note path exclusion requires interpreting tool calls (which file did this `Read`/`cat` touch?) — more adapter-specific logic than content regexes.\n\n## E. Don't rewrite at capture — gate at sync\n\nCapture verbatim (maximal fidelity), then run a broad scan at `cledger sync` that blocks the push and demands explicit redaction first.\n\n- **Pros:** Purest reading of the product intent — the local record stays exact, and scanning happens once at the actual trust boundary. False positives just prompt a human instead of corrupting the record, so you can afford a much noisier ruleset (entropy heuristics become usable here). No id-stability issues at all.\n- **Cons:** As sole defense it's a trap: \"redact before sync\" requires the purge tooling that doesn't exist, and purging notes history is the hardest operation in the system. It converts a cheap prevention problem into an expensive removal problem, at the exact moment (pushing) when users are least attentive.\n\n## My recommendation: layer A + D at capture, E as backstop\n\n- **Capture time (rewriting):** a deliberately conservative built-in ruleset — *only* unambiguous prefixed tokens and key blocks — plus optional user path/pattern rules. Redact both `content` and `raw.data` (raw is free id-wise). Version the ruleset; deterministic placeholders carrying a truncated fingerprint of the secret so identical secrets are correlatable without being recoverable. No entropy heuristics here — the false-positive cost against your preservation commitment is too high.\n- **Sync time (warning):** a broader, noisier scan that flags and requires `--force`/confirmation, never rewrites. This is where entropy detection belongs.\n- **Later:** value-based env masking (C) as an opt-in layer, and eventually the purge tooling that makes post-hoc redaction real.\n\nOne schema thought: a capture-time redaction could also append a machine-generated `redaction`-kind event (or a marker in the volatile fields) recording *that* something was scrubbed and by which ruleset version — so the record is honest about its own incompleteness, which fits the \"don't silently rewrite history\" commitment better than a bare placeholder does.\n\nWant me to spec this out in the technical design doc, or start prototyping the conservative ruleset first?","type":"text"}],"role":"assistant"},"context":{"branch":"main","cwd":"/Users/evintunador/repos/evintunador/conversation-ledger","head":"c08f650fedfb44dd1e095b61aa2bd43ed5735597","repo":"git@github.com:evintunador/conversation-ledger.git"},"conversation":{"id":"claude-code:353eecbb-eaf7-4854-a575-a9d56e290707","seq":71},"id":"ev1-9c573215ea04a47bd0c24cd368f8b239f5015fc5f19d75119380d6d39301aabe","kind":"conversation_turn","occurred_at":"2026-07-20T01:53:59.936Z","producer":{"session_id":"353eecbb-eaf7-4854-a575-a9d56e290707","source":"claude-code","tool":"cledger","version":"0.2.0"},"raw":{"data":{"cwd":"/Users/evintunador/repos/evintunador/conversation-ledger","effort":"high","entrypoint":"cli","gitBranch":"main","isSidechain":false,"message":{"content":[{"text":"I've read the design docs and the capture path (`src/adapters/claude-code.ts`, `src/store.ts`). Two architectural facts shape everything here, so let me state them first:\n\n1. **The event id is a hash of `content`** (the identity subset), while `raw` is excluded from identity. So any redaction of `content` must be *deterministic* — same source line in, same redacted output out — or rescans break idempotency and duplicate events. Meanwhile `raw